Highlights 
We characterized the gut microbiota profiles in treatment-naive 
children with ADHD.  
Faecalibacterium were decreased in children with ADHD.  
A negative correlation was found between Faecalibacterium and 
ADHD severity. 
 
ABSTRACT 
Backgrounds: Although increasing evidence suggests a role for the 
gut microbiota in neurodevelopment, the actual structure and 
composition 
of 
microbiota 
in 
children 
with 
attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) remain unclear. 
Methods: Thus, the present study aimed to define the characteristics 
of gut microbiota in treatment-naive children with ADHD and to 
assess their relationship with the severity of ADHD symptoms. 
High-throughput pyrosequencing was used to investigate the 
microbiota composition in fecal matter from 51 children with ADHD 
and 32 healthy controls (HC).  
Results: An operational taxonomical unit (OTU)-level analysis 
revealed a significant decrease in the fractional representation of 
Faecalibacterium in children with ADHD compared to HC. In 
individuals with ADHD, the abundance of Faecalibacterium was 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
5 
 
negatively associated with parental reports of ADHD symptoms. 
However, there was no significant difference in alpha diversity 
between the ADHD and control groups.  
Conclusions: This present findings support the involvement of 
microbiota alteration in psychiatric diseases and Faecalibacterium 
may represent a potential novel marker of gut microbiota in ADHD. 
Future studies are needed to validate these findings and to elucidate 
the temporal and causal relationships between these variables. 
Keyword: microbiome, inattention, hyperactivity, gut-brain axis 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
6 
 
1. Introduction 
Increasing evidence suggests that the gut microbiota plays a key 
role in the gut–brain communication axis by influencing metabolism, 
inflammation, 
the 
hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal 
axis, 
and 
neurotransmission[1, 2]. Animal studies have demonstrated that 
early-life perturbations of the developing gut microbiota can 
influence neurodevelopment, suggesting that they could potentially 
lead to adverse mental health outcomes in humans later in life[3]. 
For example, in murine models, the administration of low-dose 
antibiotics to pregnant dams induced changes in gut microbiota that 
were associated with behavioral alterations in the offspring[4]. 
Prenatal stress also disturbed the establishment of the microbiota in 
the neonatal gut, resulting in increased anxiety-like behaviors as well 
as altered cognition in adult female offspring[5]. Furthermore, 
several animal models of autism spectrum disorder (ASD) have 
shown alterations in gut microbial profiles[6, 7]. These findings 
indicate that the maintenance of microbial diversity during early life 
is important for normal development of the central nervous system. 
Several preclinical studies in humans have investigated the 
profiles of gut microbiotas in adults with common mental illnesses. 
Compared to controls, the fecal samples of patients with 
schizophrenia[8], bipolar disorder[9], and unipolar depression[10] 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
7 
 
exhibited altered microbiota composition, which was associated with 
the severity of psychiatric symptoms. Despite recent interest in the 
roles of gut–brain connections in mood, anxiety, and autism-related 
disorders, no published works have directly examined the link 
between the gut microbiota and attention deficit/hyperactivity 
disorder (ADHD)[11].  
ADHD is a common neurodevelopmental disorder characterized 
by impaired attention, hyperactivity, and difficulty controlling one’s 
impulses[12]. Although ADHD is highly heritable, accumulating 
evidence suggests that environmental factors are also involved in the 
development of this disorder[13]. Thus, the recognition of other risk 
factors for ADHD and the implementation of appropriate 
interventions may help to prevent this disorder. Clinical evidence has 
shown that probiotic treatment in early life is associated with 
improved later outcomes, such as a reduced risk of an ADHD 
diagnosis at 13 years of age[14]. Conversely, early exposure to 
antibiotics may be associated with an increased risk of ADHD[15]. 
Additionally, delivery by cesarean section, which is the main factor 
influencing early gut microbiota colonization, is thought to be a risk 
factor for ADHD[16]. These results indicate that ADHD patients are 
likely to have altered composition of the gut microbiota, which 
could conceivably contribute to their maladaptive behaviors. 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
8 
 
Therefore, a detailed assessment of the gut microbiotas of ADHD 
patients should be performed before firm conclusions are drawn. 
Given 
the 
importance 
of 
the 
gut 
microbiota 
in 
neurodevelopment, the present study investigated the human gut 
microbiota in 83 fecal samples taken from 51 treatment-naive 
children diagnosed with ADHD and 32 matched healthy 
neurotypical controls. The goals of this study were to determine 
whether there were differences in the intestinal microbiotas of the 
two groups and whether these differences were related to clinical 
symptoms. If additional studies demonstrate that these candidate 
microorganisms play an active role in either contributing to or 
ameliorating ADHD, then these are potential targets for the 
development of novel therapies for the prevention and treatment of 
ADHD. 
 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
9 
 
2. Material and Methods 
2.1 Study selection 
Juvenile patients (6–10 years of age) were prospectively 
recruited from a child and adolescent outpatient clinical center at 
Seventh People’s Hospital of Hangzhou, Zhejiang, China, from May 
2015 to December 2016. All participants were diagnosed using the 
Kiddie-SADS-Present and Lifetime Version (Kiddie-SADS-PL) 
scale, which is a semi-structured diagnostic interview conducted 
according to the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental 
Disorder-IV classification system[17]. The diagnosis of ADHD 
based on the Kiddie-SADS-PL was determined for each child by one 
of two experienced child psychiatrists (Y.Y.Z. or G.L.Z.). Subjects 
for the healthy neurotypical control group (HC) were recruited via 
advertisements and assessed with a semi-structured clinical 
interview to exclude individuals with a physical illness.  
The parents of all participating children completed the Conners 
Parent Rating Scales (CPRS) to assess the severity of ADHD 
symptoms[18]. The CPRS is a widely used rating scale that can help 
identify behavioral problems in children between 3 and 17 years of 
age. It comprises six subscales: Conduct Problems, Anxiety, 
Impulsivity–Hyperactivity, Learning Problems, Psychosomatic, and 
Hyperactivity Indices. The CPRS was also used to detect ADHD in 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
10 
 
the control subjects, who scored higher than 5 were excluded from 
our study. The dietary habits were also obtained after their parents 
finished eating behavior evaluation questionnaire, and children with 
special dietary habits (vegetarian and non-vegetarian) were not 
included in our study. The exclusion criteria for the present study 
were use of probiotics or antibiotics during the 2 months prior to the 
fecal sample collection, apparent gastrointestinal symptoms, 
depressive or anxiety symptoms (assessed by CPRS), obesity, 
common childhood atopic diseases such as asthma, eczema, allergic 
rhinitis, or other severe diseases, and/or a history or current use of 
ADHD drugs.  
After receiving a written description of the aims of this study, all 
parents provided written informed consent prior to enrollment. The 
Ethics Committee of the Seventh People’s Hospital of Hangzhou 
approved the study before the start of subject recruitment.  
 
2.2 Fecal sample collection and DNA extraction 
Parents collected fecal samples from children naïve to ADHD 
pharmacotherapies in a sterile plastic cup and then immediately 
froze the samples at -20°C at home. The samples were kept in an 
icebox that was delivered to the laboratory within 30 min, and then 
stored at -80°C. Fecal microbial DNA was extracted from 200 mg of 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
11 
 
feces using the QIAamp DNA Stool Mini Kit (Qiagen; Hilden, 
Germany) according to the manufacturer’s instructions, in 
conjunction with additional glass-bead beating steps on a 
Mini-beadbeater (FastPrep; Thermo Electron Corp.; Boston, MA, 
USA). DNA was quantified using a NanoDrop ND-2000 
spectrophotometer (Thermo Electron), and integrity and size were 
assessed via 1.0% agarose gel electrophoresis on gels containing 0.5 
mg/mL of ethidium bromide. DNA samples were stored at -20°C 
prior to analysis. 
 
2.3 Polymerase chain reaction analysis and pyrosequencing 
The bacterial 16S ribosomal RNA gene V3–V4 region was 
amplified 
with 
a 
barcoded 
primer 
set 
using 
338F 
ACTCCTACGGGAGGCAGCAG 
and 
806R 
GGACTACHVGGGTWTCTAAT. Approximately 4 µl of 5× FastPfu 
Buffer, 0.8 µl of 2.5 mM deoxyribonucleotide triphosphates dNTPs, 
0.8 µl of 5 µM reverse primer, 0.4 µl of FastPfu Polymerase, and a 
10 ng template were used for the polymerase chain reaction (PCR). 
The cycling conditions for PCR were as follows: 3 min at 95°C and 
then 27 cycles of 30 s at 95°C, 30 s at 55°C, 45 s at 72°C, and 10 
min at 72°C. Amplified DNA was sequenced using the Illumina 
MiSeq platform with a TruSeqTM DNA Sample Prep Kit (Illumina; 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
12 
 
San Diego, CA, USA). 
 
2.4 Bioinformatics and statistical analysis 
The raw pyrosequencing reads obtained from the sequencer were 
demultiplexed and quality-filtered using Trimmomatic and FLASH. 
Chimera sequences arising from the PCR amplification were 
detected and removed using UCHIME, and high-quality sequences 
were assigned to samples according to the barcodes and clustered 
into operational taxonomic units (OTUs) using QIIME (version 1.7; 
http://qiime.org/home_static/dataFiles. html). Operational taxonomic 
units (OTUs) were picked at 97% similarity cut-off. To compare the 
microbial communities in ADHD versus HC samples, alpha 
diversity and beta diversity were analyzed. Alpha diversity, which 
represents the complexity of composition within members of a group, 
was calculated using the metrics of Shannon, Simpson indices, ACE 
and Chao1. Rarefaction curves were generated based on the alpha 
diversity 
estimators. 
Beta 
diversity, 
which 
represents 
the 
between-subject similarity of microbial composition and enables 
identification of differences between samples within a group, was 
estimated by computing unweighted, weighted UniFrac distances 
and a Bray-Curtis Principal Coordinate Analysis (PCoA). 
For the beta diversity measures, principal coordinate analyses 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
13 
 
were performed at the OTU level for each sample. Microorganism 
features that distinguished fecal microbiota specific to ADHD were 
identified using the linear discriminant analysis (LDA) effect size 
(LEfSe) 
method 
(http://huttenhower.sph.harvard.edu/lefse/) 
for 
biomarker discovery. The LEfSe method uses the Kruskal–Wallis 
rank-sum test with a normalized relative abundance matrix to detect 
features with significantly different abundances between assigned 
taxa, and performs LDA to estimate the effect size of each feature; 
LDA values >2 were considered to indicate statistical significance. 
Correlations between variables were calculated using Pearson 
correlation analyses. The Benjamini and Hochberg false discovery 
rate (FDR) was used to correct for multiple tests of the hypothesis; 
and values below the FDR-corrected threshold of 0.05 were 
considered significant. All statistical analyses were performed using 
SPSS ver. 16.0 data analysis software (SPSS, Inc.; Chicago, IL, 
USA). 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
14 
 
3. Results 
3.1 Clinical characteristics and collection of 16s data 
The cohort investigated in the present study included 51 
treatment-naive ADHD patients and 32 HC subjects; the clinical data 
of the two groups are presented in Table 1. There were no significant 
differences between the groups in terms of age, gender, body mass 
index, pattern of infant feeding, mode of delivery, duration of 
pregnancy, or birth weight. However, the CPRS scores of the ADHD 
group were significantly higher than those of the HC group for the 
moral problems, learning problems, impulsive–hyperactivity, and 
hyperactivity indices. Scores of the two groups on the 
psychosomatic and anxious indices did not significantly differ. 
Illumina sequencing captured a total of 3,095,739 high-quality 
sequences from 81 fecal samples provided by participants for 
phylogenetic analysis; 1,192,290 sequences were obtained from the 
HC subjects, and 1,903,449 were obtained from the ADHD group.  
 
3.2 Diversity analysis of the fecal microbiotas in ADHD and HC 
subjects 
Based on the sequencing data, the gut microbiotas of all samples 
were classified into 779 OTUs, 16 phyla, 28 classes, 47 orders, 82 
families, 250 genera, and 520 species. The number of shared OTUs 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
15 
 
between the two groups is presented in a Venn diagram (Suppl. Fig. 
S1); 740 and 645 OTUs were identified in the ADHD and HC 
groups, respectively. 
The alpha and beta diversity values of the fecal bacterial 
communities in the ADHD and HC groups were assessed using 
various indices based on the OTU level. To determine alpha diversity, 
the mean ACE, Chao, Shannon, and Simpson reciprocal indices were 
calculated, but there were no significant differences between the two 
groups; detailed data on the estimators in each sample are presented 
in Table S1. The rarefaction curves for the numbers of observed 
operational OTUs per sample reached a plateau phase, indicating 
that most bacterial species had been sufficiently captured by the 
sequencing in all samples(Suppl. Fig. S2). In terms of beta diversity, 
unweighted and weighted UniFrac distances and a Bray–Curtis 
PCoA could not discriminate the ADHD from the HC group due to 
significant individual variation (Suppl. Fig. S3). 
 
3.3 Analyses of fecal bacterial community abundances in the ADHD 
and HC groups 
The association between fecal microbiota composition and ADHD 
was analyzed using the FDR correction for multiple tests. Phylum 
level is illustrated in Figure 1a; Firmicutes, Bacteroidetes, 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
16 
 
Proteobacteria, and Actinobacteria constituted the four dominant 
phyla in all samples, but there were no significant differences in the 
four phyla between the ADHD and HC groups. At the family level, 
there was a lower percentage of Alcaligenaceae but a greater 
abundance of Peptostreptococcaceae in the ADHD group relative to 
the HC group (Figure 1b). Comparisons of the genus composition 
revealed that three genera differed between the two groups; the 
levels of Faecalibacterium, Lachnoclostridium, and Dialister, were 
decreased in the ADHD group(Figure 1c). To explore the robust of 
our results, analyses in ADHD group were performed based on the 
route of delivery (vaginal or caesarean) and the type of early 
nutrition (breast milk or formula milk). Type of delivery has no 
significant effect on the α-diversity, β-diversity or relative 
abundance of associated ADHD taxa (Suppl. Fig. S4 and S5). 
Furthermore, within-individual or between-individual diversity was 
not significantly related to the type of feeding in our cohort (Suppl. 
Fig. S6 and S7). 
An LDA combined with LEfSe was applied to explore 
significant differences between and the relative richness of the 
bacterial communities in the ADHD and HC groups at the family 
and genus levels. At the family level, Peptostreptococcaceae, 
Moraxellaceae, Xanthomonadaceae, and Peptococcaceae were 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
17 
 
increased, whereas Alcaligenaceae was decreased in ADHD patients 
compared to the controls (Suppl. Fig. S8). At the genus level, 
Faecalibacterium, Dialister, and Sutterella, which were abundant in 
the HCs, were the key phylotypes that contributed to the differences 
in intestinal microbiota composition between the ADHD and HC 
groups(Figure 1d).  
 
3.4 Correlations between overall fecal microbiota structure and 
clinical parameters 
To investigate the associations of the microbiotas with the 
severity of clinical symptoms, ADHD patients whose microbiota 
composition differed from that of the HCs were identified. To 
accomplish this, Pearson correlation analyses were performed using 
the 18 bacterial genera that were identified as showing a significant 
case–control difference by the LefSe method. These analyses 
revealed that the abundance of Faecalibacterium was negatively 
associated with the total CPRS score and the hyperactivity index 
score(Figure 1e and 1f).
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
18 
 
4. Discussion 
To our knowledge, the present study is the first to define fecal 
microbiota composition in young children with ADHD. This study 
found differences between treatment-naïve ADHD patients and HCs 
in gut microbial composition, with the genus Faecalibacterium 
showing the greatest difference. Additionally, there were significant 
relationships 
between 
the 
fractional 
representation 
of 
Faecalibacterium and parent-reported disease measures. In contrast 
to our study, Aarts E et al.[19] observed an increased abundance of 
Bifidobacterium and Eggerthella in ADHD adults. This variation in 
composition of the gut microbiota might reflect differences in study 
population, dietary habits, age and treatment between two studies. 
The Western diet is high in fat and calories, while Chinese diets 
typically include low levels of fat, sugar and meat, which may have 
significant effects on the gut microbiota. Furthermore, as bacterial 
diversity changes with age, the inconsistent results may be explained 
by differences in age between the samples of the two studies. In 
addition, their study was limited by a lack of drug use information, 
considering that the results are likely to be affected by the use of 
psychotic medications[20]. Hence, the complexity of the issue has led 
to methodological discrepancies between studies that make it 
difficult to compare results.  
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
19 
 
The most pronounced finding in the present study was the 
general underrepresentation of Faecalibacterium in the ADHD 
group. In both animal and human studies, low Faecalibacterium 
levels are associated with a variety of unhealthy conditions including 
asthma, eczema, and allergic rhinitis[21]. It has also been suggested 
that atopic diseases are independently associated with ADHD in 
childhood, and it has been shown that individuals with these diseases 
have a 30–50% greater chance of developing ADHD compared to 
controls[22]. In the present cohort, however, children with atopic 
diseases were excluded based on a detailed medical history obtained 
from their parents, so it is unlikely that atopic disease was a 
confounding factor in this study. The anti-inflammatory properties of 
Faecalibacterium, which have been identified by in vitro and in vivo 
studies[23, 24], could influence organ systems outside the gut. A 
recent systematic review[25] provided preliminary evidence 
showing the presence of elevated markers of inflammation in an 
ADHD population. Hence, hypotheses about the biological origins 
of the association between Faecalibacterium and ADHD could 
include the impact of inflammatory cytokines on the development of 
the brain. Inflammatory cytokines released during conditions of low 
Faecalibacterium levels in the gut have the ability to cross the 
blood–brain barrier, which makes them likely candidates to play a 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
20 
 
role in the development of ADHD[26].  
Levels of the Faecalibacterium species are also lower in adults 
with psychiatric diseases compared to HCs. For example, these 
species are decreased in patients with major depressive disorder[10] 
or bipolar disorder[9]; in particular, these studies found a negative 
association between the abundance of this gut bacteria and the 
severity of disease. Subjects with apparent anxious or depressive 
symptoms were excluded from our studies, it should be noted that 
some ADHD patients may present subclinical symptoms, which 
could influence the relative abundance of Faecalibacterium in 
ADHD. 
In 
this 
case, 
the 
correlation 
between 
hyperactivity/inattention 
and 
Faecalibacterium 
may 
be 
overestimated. Genome-wide association studies revealed shared 
risk genes between ADHD and mental disorders such that more than 
20% of ADHD subjects met the criteria for depression, bipolar 
disorder, and/or generalized anxiety disorder in adulthood[27]. It is 
possible that both the lower abundance of Faecalibacterium in 
ADHD subjects and the presence of affective disorders could be 
driven by shared genetic risks in the host[28].  
In addition to scientific relevance, the association between 
Faecalibacterium and ADHD may also have clinical relevance. 
Faecalibacterium levels can be modified by a dietary approach; a 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
21 
 
diet high in insulin, amylose maize starch, soluble corn fiber, and 
resistant maltodextrin can raise Faecalibacterium levels[29, 30]. In a 
clinical study[31] of an obese population, the abundance of 
Faecalibacterium increased following long-term consumption of the 
Mediterranean diet, which is characterized by high consumption of 
vegetables, fruits, nuts, legumes, and unprocessed cereals. 
Conversely, epidemiological study[32] has shown that poor 
adherence to the Mediterranean diet is associated with increased 
prevalence of ADHD. Furthermore, the ADHD diagnosis is 
significantly higher among children who follow Western dietary 
patterns (i.e., high intakes of fat, refined sugars, and sodium and low 
intakes of fiber, folate, and omega-3 fatty acids)[33], which is 
associated with low levels of Faecalibacterium[34]. Assuming that 
the correlations identified in the present study contribute to ADHD, 
a theoretical modulation of ADHD through diet may happen not only 
via microbiota changes, and other mechanisms can be implicated 
(e.g. inflammation, lipids, amines etc). Given the influences of 
bacterial interaction networks and host genetics on the gut 
microbiota, it is difficult to predict how a particular gut microbiome 
will respond to a given dietary intervention. In any case, increasing 
gut levels of Faecalibacterium may be beneficial for ADHD 
patients. 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
22 
 
The LEfSe approach in the present study also showed that the 
levels of several genera differed. It is interesting that there was a 
significant decrease in Dialister in ADHD patients compared to the 
HCs. Previous studies[35, 36] have suggested that the activity 
dimension of temperament is predictive of ADHD symptoms in 
early adolescence. Christian et al.[37] reported that Dialister was 
positively associated with measures of activity level and 
high-intensity pleasure in toddler-aged children. In humans, 
Dialister is also linked to lower levels of interleukin (IL)-6 after 
exposure to a whole-grain diet[38]. As succinate-utilizing bacteria, 
dietary carbohydrate positively correlated with Dialister[39]. It is 
unclear why this taxon decreased in ADHD patients, though 
inflammation or unhealthy diet are possibilities. Additionally, the 
genus Sutterella was highly enriched in healthy control. A number 
of studies have investigated the possible association between 
Sutterella and autism, but results of previous studies have been 
inconsistent. Wang et al[40] showed that numbers of Sutterella are 
elevated in feces of ASD children relative to controls, whereas 
Luna et al[41] found marked decrease in intestinal mucosa. Thus, it 
is very complex to relate a specific bacteria genus/family with a 
determined set of behaviors, mechanistic studies in rodent models 
are warranted to investigate these hypotheses. 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
23 
 
The main limitation of the present study was its cross-sectional 
design, which prevents any conclusions about causality. For 
example, it remains unclear whether the observed relationships 
between 
specific 
gut 
microbiota 
genera 
and 
hyperactivity/inattention symptoms persist over time. However, the 
fecal samples of the patients were obtained prior to any 
pharmacological intervention, which suggests that the differences in 
gut microbiota composition may be native to the illness. Future 
research with repeated stool measurements using pre- and 
post-intervention strategies and considerations of symptom severity 
will be necessary to address this limitation. The present findings are 
further limited by the small sample size of the study, and the results 
will need to be evaluated using a validation cohort. 
The present study also has several strengths. First, only 
treatment-naïve ADHD juveniles were included, which excluded the 
impact of treatment on the microbiota profiles. Second, sophisticated 
statistical analyses using a relatively conservative FDR q-value were 
performed to correct for multiple tests of the hypothesis. Third, the 
use of the LDA effect size allowed for control of relative species 
abundance and provided an estimate of the magnitude of the 
observed differences. 
In conclusion, the present study identified preliminary significant 
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
24 
 
differences in microbial numbers and composition between ADHD 
patients and HCs indicating that Faecalibacterium was associated 
with ADHD and was negatively correlated with the severity of 
ADHD symptoms. Thus, studies investigating Faecalibacterium 
interventions against ADHD will be necessary. Future studies are 
needed to validate the present findings and elucidate the temporal 
and causal relationships between the gut microbiota and ADHD.
ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT
